## 3. Supported Algorithms and Use Cases\par
\par
Ultimate RNG provides a variety of algorithms, allowing you to choose the best tool for your specific performance and quality requirements.\par
\par
### 3.1. Speed-Optimized: Xoshiro256\\*\\* / Xoshiro256++ (Burst / Job)\par
\par
- **Use Case**: When maximum generation speed is required on the CPU.\par
- **Description**: Implemented using Unity's C# Job System and Burst Compiler. These generators provide remarkable single-thread and multi-thread performance, offering a perfect balance between speed and statistical quality for most game development needs.\par
\par
### 3.2. CPU-Offloading: Philox32 (Compute Shader)\par
\par
- **Use Case**: When you want to alleviate CPU load by moving generation to the GPU.\par
- **Description**: A counter-based PRNG implemented in Compute Shaders. It allows you to generate millions of random numbers directly on the GPU, keeping the CPU entirely free for main game logic. Perfect for GPU-based particle simulations and compute-heavy terrain generation.\par
\par
### 3.3. High Quality: Mt19937 & Sfmt19937 (Rust Native)\par
\par
- **Use Case**: When strict statistical quality and extensively long periods are paramount.\par
- **Description**: The standard Mersenne Twister (`Mt19937`) and the SIMD-oriented Fast Mersenne Twister (`Sfmt19937`), implemented in highly optimized native Rust. These provide the cryptographic-like gold standard for PRNG predictability and distribution.\par
\par
### 3.4. Fast & Chaotic: Sfc64 (Rust Native)\par
\par
- **Use Case**: When a strong balance of high speed, small state size, and chaotic properties is needed.\par
- **Description**: Small Fast Chaotic PRNG implemented in Rust. Excellent for initializing other states or when you need a fast native generator with a smaller memory footprint than Mersenne Twister.\par
\par
### 3.5. Ultimate Speed: Philox32 (Rust Native)\par
\par
- **Use Case**: When you need the absolute fastest generation speeds possible for extreme batch workloads.\par
- **Description**: The counter-based Philox32 PRNG implemented in native Rust. This currently delivers the highest performance of all available generators in the suite.\par
\par
> [!NOTE]\par
> **Rust Native Seed Initialization**\par
> All Rust native plugin implementations utilize the `SplitMix32` or `SplitMix64` algorithm to robustly initialize their internal state from the provided seed value.\par
\par
